{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17489590","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17489590"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:22:08+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:22:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"697"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"697","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/697"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.31,0.01,0.57,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"697"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51848"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"697","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/697"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"697"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37150"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"4139"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2779"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2784"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10660"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10947"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51848","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/51848"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 67-year-old woman is being reviewed for management of her urinary incontinence. She had presented with a six month history of leakage of urine, which was most noticeable when she coughed or sneezed. She was given advice on lifestyle measures and pelvic floor exercises. Since her initial consultation three months ago she has managed to reduce her drinking to two glasses of wine at weekends, stopped smoking and reduced her weight so that her BMI is now 28. She has hypertension and type II diabetes and takes aspirin, perindopril and metformin. Despite her improved lifestyle and thorough, regular pelvic floor exercises, her symptoms have not improved.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Persist with pelvic floor exercises and lifestyle measures","Oxybutynin","Posterior tibial nerve stimulation","Gynaecology/urology review for surgical consideration","Intradetrusor botox"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis is a clear history of stress incontinence which is best managed initially with lifestyle changes and \u003Cstrong\u003Epelvic floor exercises. \u003C/strong\u003EImportant lifestyle modifications that all women with stress incontinence should endeavour to do include weight loss (if overweight), regular exercise, optimise regular bowel habits and reduce straining. Reducing caffeine and excessive fluids can help with urge urinary incontinence. Smoking cessation would help if the patient has a regular \u0027smokers cough\u0027 as it would reduce this and the number stress incontinent episodes, however, it is less effective than pelvic floor exercises.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThese strategies have been tried for this patient and despite adherence to the advice she was given, her symptoms have persisted and a change in management needs to be considered. Once pelvic floor exercises and lifestyle modifications have failed, a \u003Cstrong\u003Ereferral to a specialist\u003C/strong\u003E (urology or gynaecology) should be considered for surgical opinion, eg a fascial sling. This discussion with the specialist might also cover other pharmacological options, such as duloxetine. Duloxetine is a serotonin-noradrenaline reuptake inhibitor and should only be considered when lifestyle and behavioural strategies have failed or if the patient is a poor candidate for surgery or if they prefer a pharmacological approach.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnticholinergics \u003C/strong\u003Elike oxybutynin help for over-active bladders and causes of \u003Cem\u003Eurge\u003C/em\u003E incontinence, however this case is clearly stress incontinence. \u003Cstrong\u003EIntradetrusor botox\u003C/strong\u003E and\u003Cstrong\u003E posterior tibial nerve stimulation \u003C/strong\u003Eare treatments for urge incontinence and may be reccommended if lifestyle modifications are not sufficient.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Stress incontinence occurs with episodes of increased intra-abdominal pressure","Key management principle of stress incontinence is pelvic floor exercises"],"references":["Santiagu SK, Arianayagam M, Wang A. Urinary incontinence pathophysiology and management outline. Australian Family Physician. 2008; 37(3): 106-110.","Wu JM. Stress Incontinence in Women.  N Engl J Med 2021; 384:2428-36."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37150"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"697"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37150","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/37150"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-08-30T09:55:50+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-08-30T09:56:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"697"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51848"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"36","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/36"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd43","name":"Urology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":